<reggrp_short_dscr>:
Delay Triggered Injection Table
------------------------------
<reggrp_public_text>:
Delay Triggered Injection Table

With DTIs a chain of frame and delays (between frames) can be configured for injection.

DTIs are intended for service activation tests, ref. ITU-T Y.1564.

Before writing to a DTI Table entry, the corresponding DTI counter must be disabled (AFI:DTI_MISC:DTI_CTRL.ENA=0).

The processing time for a chain with one frame entry and one delay entry is 12 clock cycles.
For 64 byte frames and a clock cycle of 1597 ps the maximum injection line bandwidth for a single DTI instance thus becomes 35065 Mbps.
For longer clock cycles, the injection bandwidth is proportionally smaller.

For a clock cycle of 1597 ps and 64 byte frames the total line bandwidth through each VD is limited to 35065 Mbps.
For longer clock cycles, the VD bandwidth is proportionally smaller.

Accross all DTIs and TTIs, AFI can - for 64 byte frames - inject up to half the cell bus bandwidth, provided that such bandwidth is allocated in the cell bus calendar.
I.e. for a clock cycle of 1597 ps the maximum injected bandwidth becomes 105197 Mbps.
